data.enText: something which is done with a lot of energy
data.chText: 集中力量的行动；闪击式行动

data.enText: an advertising/ a media blitz (= a lot of information about sth on television, in newspapers, etc.)
data.chText: 集中火力的广告 / 媒体宣传

data.enText: Five shops were damaged in a firebomb blitz.
data.chText: 在一次燃烧弹袭击中有五家店铺被烧毁。

data.enText: a blitz on passengers who avoid paying fares
data.chText: 对逃票乘客的突袭检查

data.enText: I've had a blitz on the house (= cleaned it very thoroughly) .
the German air attacks on Britain in 1940
to attack or damage a city by dropping a large number of bombs on it in a short time

tr: a swift and violent military offensive with intensive aerial bombardment
(American football) defensive players try to break through the offensive line

example.ex: In the autumn of 1940 London was blitzed by an average of two hundred aircraft a night...
example.tran: 1940年秋，伦敦平均每晚遭到200架飞机的空袭。

example.ex: They blitzed the capital with tanks, artillery, anti-aircraft weapons and machine guns.
example.tran: 他们动用坦克、大炮、防空武器和机关枪奇袭了首都。

value.def: If a city or building is blitzed during a war, it is attacked by bombs dropped by enemy aircraft.
value.tran: 以闪电战空袭；以闪电战攻击

value.def: The heavy bombing of British cities by German aircraft in 1940 and 1941 is referred to as the Blitz.
value.tran: 德军对英国城市的空袭，伦敦大轰炸（1940年至1941年间）

example.ex: Regional accents are still acceptable but there is to be a blitz on incorrect grammar.
example.tran: 地方口音还可以接受，但要下大力气纠正语法错误。

value.def: If you have a blitz on something, you make a big effort to deal with it or to improve it.

example.ex: On December 8 the media blitz began in earnest.
example.tran: 12月8日，一场大规模媒体宣传活动轰轰烈烈地展开了。

value.def: An advertising or publicity blitz is a major effort to make the public aware of something.
value.tran: （为吸引注意力的）大规模活动
